DIMENSION REDUCTION: PCA ANALYSIS ON IMAGE COMPRESSION¶

Dimension Reduction¶

Dimensions refer the number of input variables or features for a dataset. It can be columns or an array of points that make up a large sphere in the three-dimensional space. Dimension reduction refers to techniques that reduce the number of input variables in a dataset.

More features often make a predictive modeling task more challenging to model, more generally referred to as the curse of dimensionality. In other words, as the number of features increase, the number of samples also increases. The more features we have, the more number of samples we will need to have all combinations of feature values well represented in our sample. Therefore, it is often desirable to reduce the number of input features.

Principal Component Analysis (PCA)¶

Principal component analysis is one of the methods that can be used in dimension reduction. It is a statistical procedure to convert observations of possibly correlated features into Principal Components.

Using PCA for Image Compression¶

An image can be treated as a matrix - a grid of pixels, with values being the pixel intensities. Steps should follow as:

  • Applying PCA on the image matrix to reduce the dimensionality to a smaller number of principal components.
  • Reconstructing the image from the limited number of principal components in order to assess how much visual information retained.
  • Checking how good the reconstructed images are for different number of selected components.

About the image¶

The image is a colour image that has data in 3 channels. The shape of the data - 2791 x 4103 x 3 - it is 2791 x 4103 matrix for each channel.

Splitting the Image in R, G, B Arrays¶

A digital colored image is a combination of R, G, and B arrays stacked over each other. It is needed to split each channel from the image and extract principal components from each of them.

R, G and B stands for red, green adn blue respectively.

In [47]:
## Splitting the original image into blue, green and red arrays
blue,green,red = cv2.split(image)

Testing the image resolution by keeping different number of pricipal components¶

PCA with 25¶

In [62]:
## Applying PCA to individual arrays

pca = PCA(25)
 
#Applying to red channel and then applying inverse transform to transformed array.
red_transformed = pca.fit_transform(red)
red_inverted = pca.inverse_transform(red_transformed)
 
#Applying to Green channel and then applying inverse transform to transformed array.
green_transformed = pca.fit_transform(green)
green_inverted = pca.inverse_transform(green_transformed)
 
#Applying to Blue channel and then applying inverse transform to transformed array.
blue_transformed = pca.fit_transform(blue)
blue_inverted = pca.inverse_transform(blue_transformed)
In [63]:
## Compressing the image
img_compressed_25 = (np.dstack((blue_inverted, green_inverted, red_inverted))).astype(np.uint8)

## View compressed image
plt.imshow(img_compressed_25)

Conclusion¶

Principal component anaylsis is succesfully applied on an example image. As, conclusion the image is shown keeping in main thema with less components. If we compare the quality of the visuals:

  • PCA = 25 - The image is very blurry, it has no focus. Also, there is a serious blue disruption at the sky where it is almost white in the original picture.

  • PCA = 100 - The quality of street and buildings look improved significantly even it is still blurry. The blue disruption is still there with less volume but overall it needs improvement.

  • PCA = 250 - Street and buildings is almost same as the original picture. Blue disruption on the left is still visible but much smaller compared to 100.

  • PCA = 700 - This is the number of components required to minimize the blue disruption. It is still visible if we have a closer look but it is at a level that does not affect overall composition of the image.
